text.Taxonomy and naming:
The first formal description of this species was by Ferdinand von Mueller in 1810 and the description was published in Report on the Plants Collected During Mr. Babbage's Expedition into the North West Interior of South Australia in 1858. The specific epithet (paisleyi) honours J.C. Paisley, the private secretary to the Governor of South Australia, Sir R.G. MacDonnell.There are two subspecies:

Eremophila paisleyi  F.Muell. subsp. paisleyi which has glabrous sepals and flower stems;
Eremophila paisleyi subsp. glandulosa Chinnock  which has flower stems and sepals that are densely hairy.
